Exercise 1: Implement a Gibbs Sampler

This exercise revisits Exercise 2 from Homework #5: We assume that the data only consist of a single \(X\sim N(\mu, \sigma^2)\), and we also assume a priori that \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^2\) are independent with \(\mu\sim N(0,1)\) and \(\sigma^2\sim IG(1, 1)\). In other words, the joint prior is the product of the two marginal densities, normal for \(\mu\) and inverse gamma for \(\sigma^2\), so the prior is \[ \pi(\mu,\sigma^2) \propto \exp\left\{ -\frac{\mu^2}{2} \right\} \times (\sigma^2)^{-2} \exp\left\{ -\frac{1}{\sigma^2} \right\} \] and the likelihood is \[ L(\mu, \sigma^2) \propto (\sigma^2)^{-1/2} \exp\left\{ -\frac{1}{2\sigma^2} (X - \mu)^2 \right\}. \]

Part (a) Based on these facts, write down a function that is proportional to the posterior.

Part (b) Using part (a), derive the full conditional density for \(\mu\) given \(\sigma^2\) and \(X\).

This simply means that you should treat \(\sigma^2\) and \(X\) as constants, view the answer from part (a) as a function of \(\mu\), and identify what type of density function this function of \(\mu\) matches.

Hint: The answer should be of the form \[ \mu | \sigma^2 , X \sim N(a, b) \] where \(a\) and \(b\) are functions of \(\sigma^2\) and \(X\).

Part (c) Using part (a), derive the full conditional density for \(\sigma^2\) given \(\mu\) and \(X\).

This simply means that you should treat \(\mu\) and \(X\) as constants, view the answer from part (a) as a function of \(\sigma^2\), and identify what type of density function this function of \(\sigma^2\) matches.

Hint: The answer should be of the form \[ \sigma^2 | \mu , X \sim {\rm InvGamma}(c, d) \] where \(c\) and \(d\) are functions of \(\sigma^2\) and \(X\). The inverse gamma \((c,d)\) density function has the form \[ f(\sigma^2) \propto \left(\frac{1}{\sigma^2}\right)^{c+1} \exp\left\{ -\frac{d}{\sigma^2} \right\} \quad \mbox{for $\sigma^2>0$.} \]

Part (d) Initialize \(\mu_c = 0\) and \(\sigma^2_c=1\). Assume we observe \(X=1.2\) as in Exercise 2 of Homework #5. Implement 10,000 steps of Gibbs sampling in which each step samples a new \(\mu\) from the full conditional in Part (b) (using the most recent \(\sigma^2\) value), then samples a new \(\sigma^2\) from the full conditional in Part (c) (using the newly sampled \(\mu\) value).

To sample from \({\rm InvGamma}(c,d)\), you can use 1/rgamma(1, shape=c, rate=d). In other words, the reciprocal of a gamma random variable with shape \(c\) and rate \(d\) is distributed as \({\rm InvGamma}(c,d)\).

When you finish, you should have 10,000 bivariate \((\mu,\sigma^2)\) vectors that represent an approximate MCMC-based sample from the true posterior.

Part (e) Create a 2-dimensional scatterplot of your 10,000 recorded values of \((\mu, \sigma^2)\). Compare this scatterplot to the scatterplot that you produced in Exercise 2(d) of Homework #5 and verify that the two scatterplots look similar.

Part (f) Calculate marginal posterior sample means and standard deviations for both \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^2\) using both your Gibbs sampler (Homework #6) and your M-H sampler with normal proposal (Homework #5). Compare the two methods; they should be quite similar since they are both designed to sample from the same target posterior distribution.

Part (d)

fMu <- function(sigsq){
  rnorm(n = 1, mean = 1.2/(1 + sigsq), sd = sqrt(sigsq/(1+sigsq)))
}

fSigsq <- function(mu){
  1/rgamma(n = 1, shape = 3/2, rate = ((1/2) * (1.2-mu)^2) + 1) 
}

muC <- 0 ; sigsqC <- 1
samples <- data.frame(mu = numeric(10000), sigsq = numeric(10000))

set.seed(440)



for (i in 1:10000) {
  # Step 2: Generate proposed values
  muC <- fMu(sigsqC)
  sigsqC <- fSigsq(muC)
  
  # we dont need an acceptance probability since it will always be 1
  # this also means that we dont have a proposal, since it will always be accepted
  
  samples[i, ] <- c(muC, sigsqC)#store values of mu and sigsq current
}

gibbs_mean_mu <- mean(samples$mu)
gibbs_var_mu <- var(samples$mu)
gibbs_mean_sigsq <- mean(samples$sigsq)
gibbs_var_sigsq <- var(samples$sigsq)

# Create a summary table
comparison_table <- data.frame(
  Method = c("Gibbs", "Metropolis-Hastings"),
  Mean_Mu = c(gibbs_mean_mu, mh_mean_mu),
  Variance_Mu = c(gibbs_var_mu, mh_var_mu),
  Mean_Sigsq = c(gibbs_mean_sigsq, mh_mean_sigsq),
